The maps show the changes that have taken place at an Australian Zoo betwen 1960 and now. Summarize the information by selecting and reporting the main features and make comparisons where relevant.

The two maps illustrate how an Australian zoo has been redeveloped, comparing its layout in 1960 with its present-day configuration.
Overall, the zoo has undergone considerable modernization, with major improvements in accessibility and transport facilities. The most notable changes include the addition of two new entrances, as well as the introduction of a ferry service and a cable car system.
In 1960, the zoo could only be accessed via a harbour located in the north. The eastern area contained a picnic area next to a seal show. In the center of the zoo, there were enclosures for birds and chimpanzees situated close to a small gift shop. Meanwhile, the western section was used to house African and Australian animals.
At present, access to the zoo has been significantly improved. A new main entrance and ferry terminal have been built near the harbour, while a second entrance has been added in the south-west. A cable car now connects this southern entrance to the picnic area in the east. In addition, the gift shop has been expanded considerably.
Regarding animal areas, the central enclosures for birds and chimpanzees have been replaced by a new African animals section. The former western area, which previously housed African and Australian animals, is now used for wild animals. However, the seal show and pinic area have remained unchanged.
